Linux Commands
---------------
Text-based instructions that you type into a terminal (command line) to the linux operating systems what to do

There are some specific commands based on distribution - ubuntu, centos

<commands are case sensitive - >

Navigate to system
..................

pwd = present working directory 
ls = list files and folder in the 
ls -a  = To list all hidden files and folder
ls -l = long listing command
cd    = Move to specific directory <\home>
cd ..  = Move one step back
cd ~   = Go to home directory

Create & Manage Files/Folder

mkdir <folder_name>   = Create a folder/directory  
touch <file_name>     = To Create a empty file
cp<file_name> <folder_name> = To copy the file to give folder
mv <old_file_name> <new_file_name> = To rename the file 
rm <file_name>   = To remove the file

cp (Copy) mv (move) rm (delete)

Shortcuts
---------

=>Create multiple files in a folder

touch <file1><file2><file3>

=>Create multiple directories

mkdir -p project/src/components

=>Copy entire folder(Duplicate folder)

cp -r <folder_name><new_folder>

=>Move multiple files

mv <file1><file2><file3><folder>/

Understand loops(repetition/iteration)
----------------

=> Goal : Create 10 files

Loop version 
  for i in{1..10}; do touch file$i.txt; done

touch version
   touch file{1..10}.txt


Package Manager
...............

A Package manager is tool that helps you to 
-> Install software
-> Update software
-> Remove software
-> Manage dependencies automatically


Ubuntu : apt (Package Manager)

Use Case: Install webserver (which is used to host web application)

Commands: sudo 
1. sudo apt update     # refresh Package list
2. sudo apt upgrade    # upgrade all Package 
3. sudo apt install <package_name>      # to install a package
  -> sudo apt install -y nginx          # to install the nginx package with y auto approval 
4. sudo systemctl status <package_name> # to get the status for package

Tasks


sudo : elevated privileges. In linux sudo stands for "SuperUser Do". It is a command used in linux which allows  anormal user to execute commands with elevated 
       (aadministrator/root) privileges


Case Study 1: New server setup 
Scenario: Prepare a fresh linux server for development

You should think You need to update and upgrade system and install essential tools

Tool                          Why we need
git                           Version control
curl                          API calls/dowloads
wget                          File downloads
vim                           File editing


# Step 1 : Update System
sudo apt update

#Step 2: Upgrade packages
sudo apt upgrade -y

# Step 3: Install essential tools 
sudo apt install -y git curl wget vim

Verify 
git --version
curl --version
vim --version


Case Study 2: Web Server Deployment
Scenario: Deploy basic web server in Linux

You should think need to install and run web server(nginx/apache)

# Step 1: Install nginx
sudo apt install -y nginx

# Step 2: Status of nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx

# Step 3: Start the nginx if not Running
sudo systemctl start nginx

